f the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth ferch Owain Glendower was born in 1370, in Pembrokeshire, Wales, her father, Owain Glyndwr ap Gruffud Prince of Wales, was 22 and her mother, Margaret Hammer, was 14. She had at least 3 sons with Sir Jenkin Scudamore. She died in 1416, in Herefordshire, England, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1370–1416":"1370–1416","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1375–1434":"1375–1434","1383–1434":"1383–1434","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1349–1415":"1349–1415","1357–1420":"1357–1420","1385":"1385","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1349":"1349","1357":"1357","1434":"1434","1335":"1335","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","Abt 1385":"umbes 1385","20 September 1415":"20. september 1415","1416":"1416","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Kentchurch, Herefordsh